article.description: Dirk Nowitzki scored 16 of his 30 points in the third quarter to break open a tight game and send the Mavericks to a 103-93 victory over the winless Miami Heat on Monday night in Dallas.
article.headline: Dirk busts out in the third period
article.linkText: Nowitzki's 30 pace Mavs past winless Heat
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- Despite adding more offensive weapons before the season, the Dallas Mavericks still look to Dirk Nowitzki when they need some points. Nowitzki scored 16 of his 30 points in the third quarter to break open a tight game and send the Mavericks to a 103-93 victory over the winless Miami Heat on Monday night. "He did his job," said teammate Steve Nash, who finished with 18 points and 11 assists. "He's well-compensated for his ability to find the basket and he did his job." Nowitzki's 3-pointer with 6:23 left in the third quarter gave the Mavericks the lead for good at 58-55. Dallas closed the quarter with a 10-1 run capped by Nowitzki's 20-foot jumper with 34 seconds left and the Mavericks took a 74-64 edge into the final quarter. "I just got some good looks in the third quarter and was able to knock down some shots." Nowitzki said. "We're all capable of taking the game over at the end. We're not selfish players. We always look for the guy who's open and it was me in the third quarter." Nowitzki went 7-for-10 from the field and had three rebounds in the third quarter while being guarded mostly by Brian Grant. Nowitzki outscored the entire Heat team in the third quarter 16-14. "You've got to make Dirk drive and I didn't do a good job of that," said Grant, who had 13 points and 12 rebounds. "You can't give him airspace." Antoine Walker, Tony Delk and Antawn Jamison were all brought in before the season to help the offense. Delk had 17 points and Walker 13 points, nine rebounds and six assists for the Mavericks (3-1). "We still haven't jelled like we should, especially on the defensive end," Delk said. "It's something you need to learn as you play." Udonis Haslem had 20 points and 12 rebounds, John Wallace scored 19 points, and Lamar Odom had 17 points and nine assists for the short-handed Heat (0-4). Miami was missing key players Eddie Jones (strained right calf and cut right hand) and Dwyane Wade (left hip pointer). Samaki Walker was placed on the injured list Monday because of an injured right shoulder. The Heat signed rookie free agent guard Kirk Penney earlier Monday to bolster their bench, and Penney played 14 minutes in his NBA debut. "I'm not going to get into the moral victory thing," Heat coach Stan Van Gundy said. "What I'm interested in is starting to build an identity as a team. Even though they made a run, we hung on and didn't lose by 20." Miami carried a 26-25 advantage into the second quarter after Dallas got off to an 18-7 start. The Heat took a 50-48 halftime lead on Grant's 15-foot buzzer-beater as Miami took advantage of some listless play by the Mavericks. "(The Heat) came in here and gave us all we could handle," Antoine Walker said. "And you've got to expect that. They're hungry for a win."

Game notes
Jones and Wade are expected back by the weekend. ... The Mavericks were without rookie F Josh Howard, who's day-to-day because of a sprained right ankle. ... Penney was Miami's first substitute. He made a 3-pointer on his first shot, then missed his next five field-goal attempts. ... The Mavericks spent most of the night settling for jumpers. They took only two free throws in the first three quarters. ... Miami is off to its worst start since going 0-4 to begin the 1994-95 season. ... Dallas was called for only 10 fouls. The Mavericks' fewest last season was 14. ... Miami held a 43-36 rebounding edge, including 12-4 on the offensive boards.
